## 9. Git Conventions

### Branching
- Feature branches: `/<workarea>-<username>` (e.g. `/retrieval-jasonw`)
- Work area branches: `/<workarea>` (e.g. `/retrieval`, `/capsule-generation`, `/workspace-ui`)
- All work merges to `main` or a workarea branch via **pull request only**.

### Commits
- Commit messages must clearly describe what the commit accomplishes.
- Prefer incremental commits over large monolithic ones. If a commit is large or complex, call it out explicitly in the description.

### Pull Requests
- Every PR into `main` or a workarea branch requires **at least one reviewer**.
- PR description must detail changes and explain how a reviewer can test for expected functionality.
- Reviewers must complete reviews within **24 hours** of being tagged.

---

## 10. Project Folder Conventions

```
/backend
  /agents          # LangGraph nodes and agent logic
  /api             # FastAPI routers
  /db              # asyncpg connection, Alembic migrations, repos
  /models          # Pydantic schemas
  /services        # LLM client, embedding utilities
  /tests
/frontend          # Next.js app
/docs              # PDFs, papers, reference materials
  README.md        # Summary of each resource (one paragraph per doc)
/docker-compose.yml
/.env.example
```

- `/docs` must contain a `README.md` with a description and summary of every reference material added to the folder.
- Model checkpoints saved as `.pt` files, organized under `/checkpoints/<model_name>/epoch_<N>/` with a `README.md` describing performance. Poor-performing runs should be deleted rather than committed.

